              <h2>How the Mayan calendar converter works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool converts between the modern Gregorian calendar and
                three classic Mayan calendars: the <strong>Long Count</strong>,
                the <strong>Tzolk’in</strong> (260‑day sacred calendar), and the
                <strong>Haab</strong> (365‑day civil calendar).
              </p>
              <p>
                Internally, every date is represented as a single
                <em>day number</em> counted from the Mayan epoch. Using a
                correlation constant (by default GMT 584283), that day number is
                mapped to a proleptic Gregorian date.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Long Count structure</h3>
              <p>
                The Long Count is a mixed base‑20 / base‑18 positional system:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Units and values</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>1 kin = 1 day</li>
                  <li>1 uinal = 20 kin = 20 days</li>
                  <li>1 tun = 18 uinal = 360 days</li>
                  <li>1 katun = 20 tun = 7,200 days</li>
                  <li>1 baktun = 20 katun = 144,000 days</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Day number \(N\) from a Long Count \(B.K.T.U.Ki\) is:
                </p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
N = B·144000 + K·7200 + T·360 + U·20 + Ki</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h3>2. Correlation constant (GMT 584283)</h3>
              <p>
                To connect Mayan day numbers with our calendar, we use a
                correlation constant \(C\) that specifies which Julian Day
                Number (JDN) corresponds to the Mayan epoch (0.0.0.0.0).
              </p>
              <p>
                This converter uses the widely accepted
                <strong>GMT 584283</strong> by default, where:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
JDN = N + C
Gregorian date ⇄ JDN via standard astronomical algorithms</pre
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                Alternative options (GMT+1, GMT‑2) shift the mapping by one or
                two days to match other traditions.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Tzolk’in date calculation</h3>
              <p>
                The Tzolk’in is a 260‑day cycle combining numbers 1–13 with 20
                day names. This tool uses the conventional sequence starting
                from 4 Ajaw on the epoch.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Day names (0–19 index)</strong></p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
Imix, Ik’, Ak’bal, K’an, Chikchan, Kimi, Manik’, Lamat, Muluk, Ok,
Chuwen, Eb’, B’en, Ix, Men, Kib’, Kab’an, Etz’nab’, Kawak, Ajaw</pre
                >
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Formulas</strong> (with N = day number since epoch):
                </p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
Tzolk’in number  = ((N + 3) mod 13) + 1
Tzolk’in name id = (N + 19) mod 20</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h3>4. Haab date calculation</h3>
              <p>
                The Haab is a 365‑day cycle with 18 months of 20 days plus a
                5‑day month called Wayeb. The epoch is usually taken as 8
                Kumk’u.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Months (0–18 index)</strong></p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
Pop, Wo, Sip, Sotz’, Sek, Xul, Yaxk’in, Mol, Ch’en, Yax, Sak, Keh,
Mak, K’ank’in, Muwan, Pax, K’ayab, Kumk’u, Wayeb</pre
                >
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Formulas</strong> (with N = day number since epoch):
                </p>
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
h = (N + 348) mod 365
monthIndex = floor(h / 20)
dayInMonth = h mod 20
(if monthIndex = 18, valid dayInMonth = 0–4 for Wayeb)</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h3>5. Gregorian date conversion</h3>
              <p>
                The converter uses standard astronomical algorithms to convert
                between Gregorian dates and Julian Day Numbers (JDN), then
                applies the correlation constant:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <pre class="whitespace-pre-wrap text-xs">
N = JDN - C
Long Count = decomposition of N into baktun, katun, tun, uinal, kin
Tzolk’in & Haab = cyclic functions of N (as above)</pre
                >
              </div>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this converter historically exact?</h3>
              <p>
                Mathematically, yes: for any chosen correlation constant the
                mapping between day numbers and calendar dates is exact.
                Historically, scholars debate which correlation best matches
                ancient inscriptions and astronomical events. GMT 584283 is the
                most widely used in modern Mayanist research, which is why it is
                the default here.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why do some sites give a different date for the same Long Count?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Differences usually come from using a different correlation
                constant, or from using the Julian calendar instead of the
                proleptic Gregorian calendar for very early dates. This tool
                clearly states the correlation in use and always uses the
                proleptic Gregorian system for consistency.
              </p>

              <h3>What range of dates can I convert?</h3>
              <p>
                The underlying algorithms support a very wide range (thousands
                of years BCE to far in the future). However, the classic Long
                Count inscriptions mostly fall within a few baktuns of the
                traditional epoch, so extremely large baktun values are more of
                a mathematical curiosity than historically used.
              </p>
            </section>
